{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1bfac4ce-9963-4699-9c24-a91a876390ae","content":"There's no repo content here to reference, so here's general guidance:\n\n**Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump` (NativeAOT)**\n\n1. **Check macOS crash reports** — the OS automatically writes crash logs to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for a `.ips` or `.crash` file matching your process name/timestamp.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps** before reproducing:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/core.%P\n   ```\n   Then re-run the app. A core file will appear at `/tmp/core.<pid>`.\n\n3. **Analyze with `lldb`**:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /tmp/core.<pid> /path/to/your/nativeaot-binary\n   ```\n   Use `bt` (backtrace), `thread list`, `frame variable`, etc.\n\n4. **If SIP blocks core dumps**, you may need to boot into Recovery Mode and run `csrutil disable` (re-enable after debugging).\n\n5. **Alternative — attach live**: if you can reproduce, attach `lldb` before the crash:\n   ```bash\n   lldb /path/to/your/nativeaot-binary\n   run\n   ```\n\n**Key difference for NativeAOT**: since there's no CoreCLR runtime, `createdump` isn't bundled. You rely on OS-level mechanisms (core dumps + crash reports) instead.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"91f92aaf-ae1d-45c9-8cf6-615409aacf57","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The working directory is empty and there's no repository to search. This is a general knowledge question. Let me answer based on my knowledge about recovering crash dumps on macOS for NativeAOT apps when `createdump` is not available.","outputTokens":447,"requestId":"764B:32DB58:DE3762:1058A0A:69FE92AB"},"id":"7ca74d13-6790-4a78-a47f-bb21778d97a1","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:49:42.765Z","parentId":"d1130280-d6ae-413e-8d86-9c2e40e53840"}
